[3] Mexico (Jalisco): suspected
Date: Sat 11 Jun 2022
Source: WorldAKKAM [edited]
https://worldakkam.com/two-more-suspicious-cases-of-monkeypox-reported-in-puerto-vallarta/775516/


The Jalisco State Health Office (SSJ) announced on Saturday [11 Jun 2022] that 2 cases of suspected monkeypox were reported in the state.

These 2 cases occurred in Puerto Vallarta, and authorities have installed modules to inform and assist people with symptoms.

The 1st case of the virus was detected in a foreign male from the United States on 7 Jun 2022. After traveling to Germany, he went to his home in Texas and on 27 May 2022 to Puerto Vallarta [Jalisco, Mexico], where he went to various gay pride celebrations. Among them, a party at Mantamar Beach Club.

The suspected case reported today [11 Jun 2022] is a 40-year-old man from Toronto, Canada, who lives in Puerto Vallarta. He was at the beach club from 17 May to 4 Jun 2022.

By 7 Jun [2022], he began to show symptoms of papules and itching. It started in the head, the back of the chest, and the lower extremities. With this in mind, he was instructed to remain isolated for 21 days.

The 2nd case is a 23-year-old woman who is a resident of Zapopan and has interacted with foreigners. She began with symptoms similar to the 1st case on 31 May 2022, in addition to fever, myalgia, and joint pain.

In both cases, samples were taken and the results are still pending at the Epidemiological Diagnosis and Reference Institute (InDRE).

The 1st case in Jalisco, considered zero patient, was a man in Dallas, Texas, whose symptoms began on 30 May [2022]. He has coughs, chills, myalgia, and pustular lesions on the face, neck, and trunk. After going to a hospital in Puerto Vallarta for advice, he was asked to undergo a test to check and isolate monkeypox, he refused and fled the hospital.

After a positive case of monkeypox was confirmed by Texas health authorities and the United States notified Jalisco authorities, the Ministry of Health called people who attended the Mantamar Beach Club party where the 1st case attended. From 27 May to 4 Jun 2022, the same days that human-to-others transmission can occur.

For this reason, SSJ has stepped up measures for disease detection and timely care in corporate health units.

[Byline: August Roberts]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[A 13 Jun 2022 PAHO update (https://reliefweb.int/report/world/epidemiological-update-monkeypox-non-endemic-countries-13-june-2022) states that "in this outbreak, some documented cases have presented pustules and lesions at different stages of development, which is atypical compared to the known clinical presentation of monkeypox."
- Mod.TY]

******
[4] Canada (Quebec)
Date: Wed 15 Jun 2022
Source: CULT MTL [edited]
https://cultmtl.com/2022/06/the-monkeypox-outbreak-in-montreal-is-being-linked-to-a-super-spreader-event-in-april/


There are currently 126 confirmed cases of monkeypox in the greater Montreal area, and a total of 132 in the province of Quebec.

In a press conference yesterday [14 Jun 2022], Montreal public health director Dr Myl√®ne Drouin and Quebec interim public health director Dr Luc Boileau confirmed that all the monkeypox cases in Montreal are in men aged 20 to 63, most of them men who had sex with other men. The outbreak has been traced back to a super-spreader event in late April [2022] where there were a number of anonymous contacts, which has made the outbreak difficult to trace.

While the vast majority of cases have not been severe, 3 men were briefly hospitalized. Over 3000 doses of the smallpox vaccine -- which is effective against monkeypox -- have been administered to those close to the infected. The city has 25 000 doses ready for the target population. Even among those who've contracted monkeypox, getting the vaccine within 4 to 14 days of infection can reduce the severity of the virus [infection].

The primary symptoms of monkeypox are painful lesions around the mouth and genitals, which may be preceded or accompanied by fever, night sweats, joint or muscle pain, swollen glands, and headaches.

Montreal public health officials first addressed the emergence of monkeypox in the city in a press conference on 19 May 2022. The 1st case of monkeypox in Montreal was reported on 12 May 2022, with symptoms 1st appearing on 29 Apr 2022, and is connected to a case in the US. Monkeypox is not an STD [sexually transmitted disease] but is typically spread among sexual partners and people who live together. There had previously been cases in the UK, Spain, and Portugal, and cases have also emerged in the US.

Drouin said last month [May 2022] that the monkeypox virus is spread by close personal contact and droplets, but is not airborne, so while steps are being taken to stop the spread, there is no need for panic. It is extremely unlikely that there would be the kind of community spread in public places that occurs with COVID-19, she said.

Reporting the virus is not mandatory, but Drouin suggested consulting a doctor if symptoms appear. Isolation at home was initially said to not be necessary but is now recommended, as is wearing a mask and covering lesions to prevent transmission. While the literature on the virus suggests monitoring symptoms for 21 days, the majority of cases in Montreal have not lasted nearly that long.

[Byline: Lorraine Carpenter]

