Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[The Uberl√¢ndia case is reported to have died. The report does not state explicitly that the death was due to monkeypox (MPX) virus infection or if there were any underlying medical conditions or secondary infections. If this is a death from MPX virus infection, it is the 1st report of an MPX death in non-endemic countries that ProMED has received.

The West African MPX virus clade, the clade that is circulating in this outbreak, has a 1% case fatality rate reported in Africa but obviously is much lower among the hundreds of cases occurring outside of Africa currently. - Mod.TY]

******
[7] United Kingdom
Date: 15 Jun 2022
Source: UK Government [edited]
https://www.gov.uk/government/news/monkeypox-cases-confirmed-in-england-latest-updates


The UK Health Security Agency (UKHSA) has detected 52 additional cases of monkeypox in England, one additional case in Scotland, and one in Wales. This brings the total number confirmed in the UK to 524, as of 14 Jun 2022.

There are currently 504 confirmed cases in England, 13 in Scotland, 2 in Northern Ireland, and 5 in Wales.

Anyone can get monkeypox, particularly if you have had close contact, including sexual contact, with an individual with symptoms. Currently, most cases have been in men who are gay, bisexual, or have sex with men.

Contact a sexual health clinic if you have a rash with blisters and you've been either:
- in close contact, including sexual contact, with someone who has or might have monkeypox (even if they've not been tested yet) in the past 3 weeks.
- to West or Central Africa in the past 3 weeks.

